    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-10-15T13:44:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-10-15T13:44:00-05:00" n="535"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d535">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">882.20/620: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hibbard</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Monrovia</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-10-15T18:00:00-00:44"
                            >October 15, 1942—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received October 16—1:12 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>348. From McBride. In final conversation with Secretary Simpson this morning in
                    company of Hibbard, he gave me a copy of a memorandum of his conference with
                    German Consul today. Consul has requested Berlin to ask Vichy to send a French
                    plane from the Ivory Coast for him and his staff to arrive here about October
                    25. Consul stated that he would much prefer to await this plane only other
                    alternative being to go to Cape Palmas in American amphibian. He did not wish to
                    travel in an enemy plane and in any event, due to his health, he could not cover
                    the distance on foot from Cape Palmas to Abidjan. Simpson acquiesced in this
                    plan and the Liberian Government has already granted request for French plane to
                    come to Monrovia and Vichy Consul has so informed Vichy.</p>
                <p>Will see President Barclay tonight and leave by Clipper October 17.
                    [McBride.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hibbard</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
